<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Colonial_era_.2816th.E2.88.9219th_centuries.29">Colonial era (16th−19th centuries)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Christianization&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Colonial era (16th−19th centuries)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="rellink">Further information: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civilizing_mission" title="Civilizing mission">Civilizing mission</a></div>
<div class="rellink boilerplate seealso">See also: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christianisation_of_Goa" title="Christianisation of Goa">Christianisation of Goa</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Our_Lady_of_Guadalupe_Churhc,_Calle_69_n53_-Av.6,_Venustiano_Carranza,_Federal_District,_Mexico08.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/Our_Lady_of_Guadalupe_Churhc%2C_Calle_69_n53_-Av.6%2C_Venustiano_Carranza%2C_Federal_District%2C_Mexico08.jpg/220px-Our_Lady_of_Guadalupe_Churhc%2C_Calle_69_n53_-Av.6%2C_Venustiano_Carranza%2C_Federal_District%2C_Mexico08.jpg" width="220" height="164" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/Our_Lady_of_Guadalupe_Churhc%2C_Calle_69_n53_-Av.6%2C_Venustiano_Carranza%2C_Federal_District%2C_Mexico08.jpg/330px-Our_Lady_of_Guadalupe_Churhc%2C_Calle_69_n53_-Av.6%2C_Venustiano_Carranza%2C_Federal_District%2C_Mexico08.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/Our_Lady_of_Guadalupe_Churhc%2C_Calle_69_n53_-Av.6%2C_Venustiano_Carranza%2C_Federal_District%2C_Mexico08.jpg/440px-Our_Lady_of_Guadalupe_Churhc%2C_Calle_69_n53_-Av.6%2C_Venustiano_Carranza%2C_Federal_District%2C_Mexico08.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Our_Lady_of_Guadalupe_Churhc,_Calle_69_n53_-Av.6,_Venustiano_Carranza,_Federal_District,_Mexico08.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf19/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Evangelization of Mexico</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The expansion of the Catholic <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portuguese_Empire" title="Portuguese Empire">Portuguese Empire</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish_Empire" title="Spanish Empire">Spanish Empire</a> with a significant role played by Catholic missionaries led to the Christianization of the indigenous populations of the Americas such as the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aztec" title="Aztec">Aztecs</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inca" title="Inca" class="mw-redirect">Incas</a>. Large number of churches were built.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23"><span>[</span>23<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24"><span>[</span>24<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Later waves of colonial expansion such as the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scramble_for_Africa" title="Scramble for Africa">Scramble for Africa</a> or the struggle for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_colonies_in_India" title="European colonies in India" class="mw-redirect">India</a>, by the Netherlands, Britain, France, Germany and Russia led to Christianization of other native populations across the globe such as the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas" title="Indigenous peoples of the Americas">Indigenous peoples of the Americas</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filipino_people" title="Filipino people">Filipinos</a>, Indians and Africans led to the expansion of Christianity eclipsing that of the Roman period and making it a truly global religion.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25"><span>[</span>25<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="America">America</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Christianization&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: America">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The fact that the American colonies were English colonies meant that colonists would be predominantly <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protestantism" title="Protestantism">Protestant</a>. Even colonists with non-English backgrounds—Scots, Scotch Irish, Germans, Dutch, French, and Swedes—were mostly Protestant. Thus Protestantism as a religious force shaped the mind of colonial America.</p>
<p>It wasn't until the nineteenth century that Roman Catholics became a numerically significant segment of American life, due to large-scale immigration.</p>
<table class="metadata plainlinks ambox mbox-small-left ambox-content" role="presentation">
<tr>
<td class="mbox-image"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg" class="image"><img alt="[icon]" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/20px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png" width="20" height="14" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/30px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/40px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png 2x" /></a></td>
